There are two main causes of conformity, and they are: To be accepted by a group, one must adopt the views and practices held by the majority of its members, a phenomenon known as "social influence." Conforming to the standards of a group, whether they be stated or unstated, is a common way for individuals to ensure their behavior does not lead to social exclusion. The normative impact happens even if there is some uncertainty about the information. There are three elements that affect compliance, and they are as follows: Greater social pressure is often applied to people by organizations of a greater size. When everyone in a group thinks the same way, they are more likely to act in the same way. People are more prone to adopt the values and norms of a group that is seen as elite or influential. 